They come down in groups small enough to be deniable and large enough to be counted, hand in weapons that are logged and vanish, and receive papers whose ink smells fresh. Not all come; a remnant stays up where amnesties do not reach. But the war, as an institution of yours, ends this season — and its survivors become the political road's hardest, quietest cadres.

Committees for employment, a clinic that keeps no records, evening schools where a man can finish the studies the DFS interrupted. Some of the returned want politics; more want quiet; all of them are watched, and know it, and teach the young ones how to be watched gracefully — the era's most transferable skill.
